                    <span>I've just discovered Rosewater and Trout in Vonnegut's book Slaughterhouse-Five....I'm interested to see what comical situations they get into in this book.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">eccentric, naive, and often rather dull</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>2</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      /
                      <span>19</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2004-05-26</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>After greatly enjoying some Vonnegut sci-fi, I was perhaps looking for the wrong thing with this book.  It is a weird story about a nutty millionaire, who is in danger of losing his money to an assembly of the sleaziest twits you could possibly imagine.  While there are many very funny asides, such as his love of Kilgore Troustian conceptions or the characterizations of the evil guys (one's posterior is "luminous when wet"), the plot is weak and far-fetched.  For example, Rosewater's  grandfather built his massive fortune by buying companies in accordance with their acronyms from the Bible's text!  That is too silly to be satire.  Moreover, Vonnegut's laments about the coldness and brutality of American capitalism are sentimental and even ignorant.  He seems to have an obsession with rich people and money.
<br />
<br />Not recommended.</span>
                  
